<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0006 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0043EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-LouisianaAt-A-Glance     03-08 0249</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Louisiana At-A-Glance,260</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from Louisiana to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 63   Super delegates: 8   Total: 71   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Saturday, March 26 and Saturday, June 4   Louisiana's 63 pledged national convention delegates will beallocated among Democratic presidential candidates in proportion tothe results of the March 8 primary.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 41   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Tuesday, March 8 and Sunday, April 17   Louisiana Republicans allocate their national conventiondelegates among presidential candidates based on results of theMarch 8 primary.   Three delegates in each of the state's 8 congressional districtsare awarded on a winner-take-all basis to the candidate receivingthe most votes in a district. The remaining 17 delegates at-largeare awarded to candidates in proportion to the results of theprimary statewide.   Candidates need to receive at least 20 percent of the statewidevote to qualify for at-large delegates.   Presidential candidates submit slates for at-large delegates tothe state party by Feb. 15. After the primary, the presidentialcandidates choose their delegates from these slates by April 7.</TEXT></DOC>